          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Inversely proportional to the initial muscle fiber length</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 67-year-old man with a history of congestive heart failure is admitted to the cardiology ward for worsening dyspnea and pedal edema. The attending cardiologist explains to the patient and his family how the heart&#39;s ability to pump blood is influenced by changes in ventricular volume, relating this to the Frank-Starling law of the heart. According to the Frank-Starling law, how is the force of cardiac muscle contraction related under physiological conditions?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5101609",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33673,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Directly proportional to the initial muscle fiber length</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Correct. The <strong>Frank-Starling law</strong> states that the <strong>force</strong> of <strong>cardiac muscle contraction</strong> is <strong>directly proportional</strong> to the <strong>initial length</strong> of the <strong>cardiac muscle fibers</strong> (or end-diastolic volume), which correlates with <strong>ventricular filling</strong>. This relationship <strong>allows</strong> the <strong>heart</strong> to <strong>adjust</strong> its <strong>pumping ability</strong> based on the <strong>volume</strong> of <strong>blood returning</strong> to it.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. The <strong>force</strong> of <strong>contraction</strong> is directly related to the <strong>degree</strong> of <strong>contraction</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. While <strong>temperature</strong> can <strong>affect</strong> the <strong>speed</strong> of <strong>muscle contraction</strong> and <strong>enzymatic activity</strong>, the <strong>Frank-Starling law</strong> specifically relates the <strong>force</strong> of <strong>contraction</strong> to the <strong>initial muscle fiber length</strong>, not directly to temperature.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. According to the <strong>Frank-Starling law</strong>, the <strong>force</strong> of <strong>muscle contraction</strong> <strong>increases</strong> with an <strong>increase</strong> in the <strong>initial length</strong> of the <strong>muscle fibers</strong>, not inversely. This principle is fundamental to the <strong>heart&#39;s ability</strong> to <strong>adapt</strong> to <strong>varying volumes</strong> of <strong>venous return</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understand the <strong>Frank-Starling law&#39;s</strong> <strong>principle</strong> that the <strong>force</strong> of <strong>cardiac muscle</strong> <strong>contraction</strong> is <strong>directly proportional</strong> to the <strong>initial muscle fiber length</strong>, which is essential for the <strong>physiological adaptation</strong> of the <strong>heart</strong> to <strong>changes</strong> in <strong>venous return</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/29/screenshot-2024-02-29-161448.jpg\" style=\"height:97px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical Physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 546</span></strong></span></span></p>",
