      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Ans. B) 1- Increased myosin ATPase activity; 2- Myosin light chain phosphatase dephosphorylates myosin, leading to relaxation</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Option B:</strong> Correct. 1- Increased myosin ATPase activity; 2- Myosin light chain phosphatase dephosphorylates myosin, leading to relaxation</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><br>•&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Myosin ATPase activity increases during contraction and allows cross-bridge cycling.<br>•&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MLCP removes phosphate from myosin light chain, ending contraction and allowing relaxation.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><br><strong>Steps of Smooth Muscle Contraction and Relaxation</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><br><strong>Contraction:</strong><br>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Stimulus</strong> (e.g., neurotransmitter, hormone) increases <strong>intracellular Ca²⁺.</strong><br>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ca²⁺ binds to <strong>calmodulin</strong>, forming a <strong>Ca²⁺-calmodulin complex</strong>.<br>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This complex activates <strong>MLCK (Myosin Light Chain Kinase).</strong><br>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MLCK <strong>phosphorylates myosin light chains</strong>, increasing <strong>myosin ATPase activity.</strong><br>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Myosin binds to actin</strong> → cross-bridge cycling → <strong>contraction.</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><br><strong>Relaxation:</strong><br>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ca²⁺ levels <strong>decrease</strong> via pumps (SERCA).<br>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Reduced Ca²⁺ levels <strong>inactivate MLCK.</strong><br>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;MLCP (Myosin Light Chain Phosphatase)</strong> <strong>dephosphorylates </strong>myosin light chain.<br>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dephosphorylated myosin detaches from actin → <strong>relaxation.</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>#Extra Edge:&nbsp;</strong>Sequence of events in contraction and relaxation of smooth muscle:</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/29/16.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"613\"></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong><br><br><strong>Option A: Incorrect.</strong> A. 1 - Increased myosin ATPase activity; 2 - Myosin light chain phosphatase causes phosphorylation of myosin leading to contraction<br>Part 1 is correct—increased myosin ATPase is essential for contraction.<br>Part 2 is wrong—MLCP (myosin light chain phosphatase) dephosphorylates, not phosphorylates, and leads to relaxation, not contraction.<br><br><strong>Option C: Incorrect.&nbsp;</strong><br>Part 1 is wrong—decreased ATPase means reduced contraction, not normal function.<br>Part 2 is wrong—MLCK (myosin light chain kinase) causes contraction, not relaxation.<br><br><strong>Option D: Incorrect.</strong>&nbsp;<br>Part 1 is wrong—low ATPase = low contractile force.<br>Part 2 is wrong—dephosphorylation by MLCP leads to relaxation, not contraction<br><br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">To understand the biochemical mechanisms underlying smooth muscle contraction, specifically the roles of myosin ATPase activity and myosin light chain phosphatase in the regulation of muscle tone.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Ref: Ganong's Review of Medical physiology 25th edition, pg no: 116</strong></p>",
