          "id": 31860,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Intercalated discs</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31861,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Dense bodies</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31862,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Nissl granules</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31863,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Calmodulin</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 55-year-old male with a history of hypertension presents to the emergency department with acute chest pain.In the context of smooth muscle anatomy, which of the following structures is equivalent to the Z-line found in striated muscle, playing a key role in the contraction mechanism of smooth muscle within the vascular wall?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8797880",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33672,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Dense bodies</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Correct. <strong>Dense bodies</strong> in smooth muscle serve a function analogous to <strong>Z-lines</strong> in <strong>striated muscle</strong>, <strong>anchoring actin filaments</strong> and <strong>enabling muscle contraction</strong> through their connection to the <strong>cytoskeleton</strong> and <strong>cell membrane</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Dense bodies</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"> in the <strong>smooth muscle</strong> are diagrammatically shown as:</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/29/21_NUycqun.jpg\" style=\"height:302px; width:700px\" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. Intercalated discs are specialized junctions found <strong>between cardiac muscle cells</strong>, facilitating <strong>synchronized contraction</strong>. They are not present in smooth muscle and thus are not equivalent to Z-lines.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. <strong>Nissl granules</strong> are <strong>rough endoplasmic reticulum</strong> structures found in neurons, involved in <strong>protein synthesis</strong>. They are unrelated to muscle contraction mechanisms and do not have an equivalent role to Z-lines in smooth muscle.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. <strong>Calmodulin</strong> is a <strong>calcium-binding</strong> messenger <strong>protein</strong> that plays a crucial role in the <strong>calcium signaling pathway</strong> within smooth muscle cells, particularly in the <strong>contraction process.</strong> However, it does not serve a structural role analogous to Z-lines.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Identify the structural components of <strong>smooth muscle</strong>, particularly <strong>dense bodies</strong>, and their role in <strong>muscle contraction</strong>, analogous to <strong>Z-lines</strong> in <strong>striated muscle</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical Physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 115</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
