          "id": 31892,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">&lt; 1 ms</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31893,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">5 ms</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31894,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">50 ms</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31895,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">300 ms</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">A 55-year-old patient with hypertension is being evaluated for medication-induced smooth muscle relaxation as a treatment strategy. What is the typical duration of an action potential in smooth muscle, which is significant for pharmacological interventions?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2448630",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33675,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. D) 300 ms</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Correct. The <strong>duration</strong> of <strong>action potential</strong> in a <strong>smooth muscle</strong> is around <strong>300 ms</strong> with a <strong>plateau phase</strong> (range of 100-400 ms), depending on the type, <strong>location</strong> and <strong>function</strong> of the <strong>smooth muscle fibers</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">The duration of action potential will be <strong>shorter</strong> in a <strong>skeletal muscle</strong> (around <strong>2-5 ms</strong>); The <strong>action potential duration</strong> will be <strong>longer</strong> (long lasting) in a <strong>smooth muscle</strong>, compared to that of skeletal muscle</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. A duration of less than 1 ms is characteristic of <strong>very rapid action potentials</strong>, such as those found in certain types of neurons, but not in smooth muscle cells where action potentials are significantly longer due to a plateau phase.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. An <strong>action potential duration</strong> of <strong>5 ms</strong> is <strong>too short</strong> for <strong>smooth muscle cells</strong>. Smooth muscle action potentials, especially those with a <strong>plateau phase</strong>, <strong>last much longer</strong> to facilitate <strong>prolonged contraction</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. <strong>Although 50 ms</strong> represents a <strong>longer duration</strong> than the previous options, it <strong>still</strong> <strong>falls short</strong> of the typical duration range for smooth muscle action potentials, which includes a plateau phase extending the duration.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Recognize the <strong>prolonged duration</strong> of <strong>action potentials</strong> in <strong>smooth muscle</strong>, typically <strong>around 300 ms</strong>, which is crucial for understanding the pharmacodynamics of drugs affecting smooth muscle activity.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 116, Guyton and Hall </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia edition (13<sup>th</sup> Edition), pg no: 178</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
